@{APEN 2}@{B}Tips & Troubleshooting@{UB}@{APEN 1}

@{APEN 2}@{B}General Tips@{UB}@{APEN 1}
============

- @{B}Always enable backups@{UB} for large or recursive operations. You can
  safely experiment knowing you can restore the original layout.
- @{B}Start small:@{UB} Try tidying a single folder first to see how the settings
  affect icon layout and window size before processing an entire
  partition.
- @{B}Save your settings:@{UB} Once you find a configuration you like, use @{B}Save
  Settings@{UB} from the menu so you can quickly reload it later.
- @{B}Live preview trick:@{UB} Keep a folder window open in Workbench while you
  run iTidy on that folder. This lets you fine-tune settings before
  committing to a long recursive run across many subfolders. During
  processing, some icons may temporarily overlap until all icons in that
  folder have been repositioned; for best results, allow iTidy to finish
  the folder it's currently working on before cancelling. Once a folder
  is complete, you can safely stop a long recursive run if you decide
  you've seen enough. Window size and position might be cached by
  Workbench until you close and reopen the drawer, but you can
  immediately see how icons are arranged.
- @{B}To see window changes:@{UB} Close all affected folders before running
  iTidy, then reboot after processing completes to see the new window
  sizes and positions.

@{"Back to Tips & Troubleshooting" LINK TIPS_TROUBLESHOOTING}


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ICONS_APPEAR_MISALIGNED_COLOR_ICON_ICON_LIBRARY_ISSUE "Icons Appear Misaligned (Color Icon / icon.library Issue)"
@PREV GENERAL_TIPS
@NEXT WINDOW_POSITIONS_NOT_UPDATING
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Tips & Troubleshooting@{UB}@{APEN 1}

@{APEN 2}@{B}Icons Appear Misaligned (Color Icon / icon.library Issue)@{UB}@{APEN 1}
=========================================================

If some icons appear misaligned after tidying, but others look fine, this
is usually caused by an outdated icon.library that cannot display modern
color icons correctly.

@{B}What happens:@{UB} OS 3.5+ color icons require icon.library v44 or higher. On
older systems (Workbench 3.0/3.1 with the original icon.library), these
icons display as tiny placeholder images--often just a few pixels tall.
iTidy reads the @{I}actual@{UI} icon dimensions and positions icons correctly, but
Workbench displays the wrong size, making icons appear misaligned.

@{B}Solution:@{UB} Update your icon.library to v44 or newer. Updated libraries are
available from Aminet or as part of OS 3.5/3.9/3.2 upgrades.
Alternatively, convert color icons to NewIcons or classic format if you
prefer to stay on an older Workbench.

@{B}Note:@{UB} iTidy reads and positions icons according to their real dimensions.
On older systems, the visual misalignment is caused by how classic
icon.library versions render modern color icons, rather than by iTidy's
layout logic.

@{"Back to Tips & Troubleshooting" LINK TIPS_TROUBLESHOOTING}


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE WINDOW_POSITIONS_NOT_UPDATING "Window Positions Not Updating"
@PREV ICONS_APPEAR_MISALIGNED_COLOR_ICON_ICON_LIBRARY_ISSUE
@NEXT IF_BACKUP_OR_RESTORE_DOESN_T_WORK_AS_EXPECTED
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Tips & Troubleshooting@{UB}@{APEN 1}

@{APEN 2}@{B}Window Positions Not Updating@{UB}@{APEN 1}
=============================

After restoring a backup or running iTidy, window positions may not appear
to change immediately.

@{B}Cause:@{UB} Workbench caches window geometry for open folders.

@{B}Solution:@{UB} Close and reopen the affected folder windows. In some cases, you
may need to restart Workbench or reboot for changes to take effect.

@{"Back to Tips & Troubleshooting" LINK TIPS_TROUBLESHOOTING}


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE IF_BACKUP_OR_RESTORE_DOESN_T_WORK_AS_EXPECTED "If Backup or Restore Doesn't Work as Expected"
@PREV WINDOW_POSITIONS_NOT_UPDATING
@NEXT SLOW_PROCESSING_ON_LARGE_FOLDERS
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Tips & Troubleshooting@{UB}@{APEN 1}

@{APEN 2}@{B}If Backup or Restore Doesn't Work as Expected@{UB}@{APEN 1}
=============================================

@{B}Check the following:@{UB}

- LhA must be installed in "C:" directory
- Sufficient free disk space for archives (backups) or extraction
  (restores)
- The original folder paths must still exist when restoring
- Check "PROGDIR:logs/" for detailed error messages

@{"Back to Tips & Troubleshooting" LINK TIPS_TROUBLESHOOTING}


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE SLOW_PROCESSING_ON_LARGE_FOLDERS "Slow Processing on Large Folders"
@PREV IF_BACKUP_OR_RESTORE_DOESN_T_WORK_AS_EXPECTED
@NEXT ICONS_DON_T_OPEN_UNABLE_TO_OPEN_YOUR_TOOL
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Tips & Troubleshooting@{UB}@{APEN 1}

@{APEN 2}@{B}Slow Processing on Large Folders@{UB}@{APEN 1}
================================

Processing thousands of folders recursively is naturally time-consuming,
especially on real Amiga hardware with mechanical drives.

@{B}Tips:@{UB}

- iTidy can be left running unattended for large operations
- Avoid running other disk-intensive programs simultaneously
- For very large collections, consider breaking the work into chunks
  (e.g., "WHDLoad:Games" then "WHDLoad:Demos") rather than processing
  everything at once

@{"Back to Tips & Troubleshooting" LINK TIPS_TROUBLESHOOTING}


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ICONS_DON_T_OPEN_UNABLE_TO_OPEN_YOUR_TOOL "Icons Don't Open ("Unable to open your tool")"
@PREV SLOW_PROCESSING_ON_LARGE_FOLDERS
@NEXT SAFETY_DISCLAIMER
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Tips & Troubleshooting@{UB}@{APEN 1}

@{APEN 2}@{B}Icons Don't Open ("Unable to open your tool")@{UB}@{APEN 1}
=============================================

This error means the icon's default tool path points to a program that
doesn't exist on your system.

@{B}Solution:@{UB} Use @{B}Fix Default Tools...@{UB} to scan for missing tools and repair
them. See the Default Tool Analysis section for details.

@{"Back to Tips & Troubleshooting" LINK TIPS_TROUBLESHOOTING}


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE SAFETY_DISCLAIMER "Safety & Disclaimer"
